Namaste.

Thanks for your clarification. I think because of your high spiri=
tual position, devotion is enough. While for common people like me, pronunc=
iation matters. (You have opined the same, saying it may be needed in the b=
eginning.) Personally I have found correct pronunciation to be very importa=
nt, and even it happened that I adopted a pronunciation out of my experienc=
e and later came to know it being correct gramatically!

I also feel that i=
t is a will of the divinity that you will share the correctness of Sanskrit=
 (among other wisdom) and that is why the divinity gives you insights about=
 it.

I have got two questions -

1) As you said -

"It is "sin(g)ha" with =
g silent."

I guess it will pronounce exactly like English words king, sing=
, ring, ping etc., am I correct here?

2) A question about Ganapati Atharva=
 Shirsham. In the end of the para where Ganapati is praised as Brahma, Vish=
nu, Rudra, Indra etc., it ends with -

"... tvam brahma bhur-bhuvas-suvarom=
"

All other sources I came across says 'svarom' instead of 'suvarom'. I su=
ppose it talks about the three worlds bhuh, bhuvah and suvah; and this thir=
d one in other sources are being mentioned as 'svah' instead of 'suvah'. In=
teresting to note that in the Gayatri mantras available on the net it is me=
ntioned as either suvah / svah (variations). However I learned the Gayatri =
in the past as 'svah'.

But you have chosen 'suvah' (not 'svah') and even i=
n the homam manual, while lighting the fire, and even purifying fire with e=
igth drops of ghee, you have always chosen 'suvah'.

So I am sure that ther=
e must be a definite reason that you prefer 'suvah' and not 'svah'. Could y=
ou please explain the reason a bit. Also, if 'suvah' is correct, shall we a=
lso use it in the Gayatri mantra?

Thanks
Tanvir
