  Namaste,

  Your keen obse=
rvation is impressive!



  Yes, that anusvara is pronounced by most schola=
rs as "gum" or "gam". But, given that it is supposed to be just a nasal sou=
nd, I am not convinced by the explicit occurrence of the consonant "g". IMH=
O, it is definitely a Kali yuga corruption.

  *        *        *

  This =
one is tricky. But there are more common sounds, e.g. vowel ai as in "aim" =
beeja and "aindri" word, vowel ru/ri as in "rushi" or "rishi", hanging cons=
onant "t" at the end of "prachodayaat" etc. Most people do not pronounce th=
ese correctly. These occur in simple words, as opposed to this anuswara whi=
ch occurs in complex Veda mantras only. There are several such things where=
 no single region of India got it right. Different parts of India are corre=
ct in different things.

  Fortunately, the correct pronunciation of all th=
ese sounds is confidently and accurately derivable based on grammar rules e=
tc, if only one applies oneself and thinks straight. Over the years, I have=
 identified several of these, convinced myself 100% on each (except the anu=
swara where I am not 100% sure) and switched my pronunciation accordingly.
=

  However, now I am 100% convinced that pronunciation is only 1% of the th=
ing and devotion and sincerity are far more important, though correct pronu=
nciation may be initially useful.

  So I am not that motivated to correct =
people's pronunciation. But, given that several insights came to me on this=
 over the years, it is probably one of my dharmas to share them with the wo=
rld before I leave. I will try to do it soon. I thought of making a youtube=
 video on "pronunciation of tricky Sanskrit sounds" many years ago (showing=
 my face and a white board). Perhaps time has come to just do it.



  *   =
     *        *

  Coming back to this anuswara:

  Bindu before p, ph, b, =
bh is pronounced as one nasal (m); bindu before t, th, d, dh is pronounced =
as another nasal (n); bindu before k, kh, g, gh is pronounced as another na=
sal; bindu before ch, chh, j, jh is pronounced as another nasal, etc.

  My=
 take is that bindu before y, r, l, v, sh, Sh, s, h is to be pronounced as =
the first one again, i.e. as the nasal before k, kh, g, gh.

  Take the man=
tra "tanno nArasi{M}haH prachodayAt", where {M} is this anuswara. A lot of =
scholars pronounce this as "tanno nArasiguMhaH prachodayAt". IMHO, that is =
way off and has an extra syllable. You are better off just pronouncing it a=
s "tanno nArasimhaH prachodayAt", i.e. pronounce {M} as "m" or the nasal be=
fore p, ph, b, bh.

  But better IMHO is to pronounce it as the nasal befor=
e g. Start off as though you are saying "tanno nArasinghaH prachodayAt", su=
ppress "g" when about to say it, and jump directly to "h". That is what I d=
o. This allows you to pronounce the correct nasal. Unless we are about to s=
ay, k, kh, g or gh, we can't say that nasal. Of course, in some languages (=
e.g. Vietnamese), that nasal occurs independently and those people can pron=
ounce it well.

  BTW, if you end up letting out a bit of "g" instead of su=
ppressing it completely and jumping to "h", then you end up getting "singha=
", which is another common corruption of "si{M}ha".

  To put it simply: Th=
e correct pronunciation is neither "sinha" nor "simha" nor "singha". It is =
"sin(g)ha" with g silent.

  Best regards,
  Narasimha
